metadata.name: The Binding String #40
metadata.description:
........._____.........
......./+_+_+_+\.......
..|.../+/.._..\+\...\/.
..\|.|+|..|x|..|+|..|..
.\/___\+\.|_|./+/__/_|.

100% code. Typography hand-made by @nathansonic

+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+

Press s to save.
Click the screen to pause the animation.

+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+

This piece explores the interplay of our concepts of communication and the web.

The transaction hash creates the randomization but it’s also the protagonist in this story. It dons the stone and halo as the key for how the blockchain speaks to you.

The transaction hash is brought purposefully into the piece in order to recognize its significance almost as a deity in the generative process. It’s the one thin string binding our real-life experience with blockchain.

+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+

If you want a larger scene with more detail (larger resolution), zoom out using the browser zoom. Be careful as the more you zoom out the more ground elements will be created to fill the scene.

+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+

Pricing - Dutch auction
The pricing is a Dutch auction set at 4 - 3 - 3. 433 is the number of randomized variables in the piece.

Mint amount
The mint amount is 170. 170 is the number of unique elements multiplied by 10.

+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+

The binding string started with a focus on maximizing the possible variations.

This has led to the project having 433 randomizable variables that tweak the scene to create insane variation. A lot of this variation is very subtle, but it’s there.

Random variables: 433 = 281 (rand int) + 62 (rand float) + 90 (Perlin noise).

+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+

The binding string has multiple layered scene elements. Some of these elements interact. Plants are forced back by the halo, elements closer to the central glowing rock reflect more light etc. There are 17 elements in total.

Here are some of the elements that characterize the narrative and aesthetic:
Stone circle
Planets
Plants (trees, bushes)
Fireflies
Animated halo
Glyph text
A smart, fully randomized custom palette creator.
Geometric shapes
Atmosphere scenarios ( day, evening, night, foggy)
Rocks
Mossy-ness
Crystal Geodes
Skewed hills
Ground elements (mud, grass)
Math based lighting
Galaxy lines
Shadow dust

+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+

Extra special thanks to @nathansonic for his support, feedback, and code editions.

+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+

3rd party code used:
Various bits by @nathansonic, including a custom palette creator.
Noisejs - github.com/josephg/noisejs - Perlin noise generator
Twgl - github.com/greggman/twgl.js - A small webGL helper.

+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+

metadata.name: what's left of what's left #45
metadata.description:
"The images is not a closed field of knowledge; it is a whirling, centrifugal field. It is not a fiedl of knowledge like any other; it is a movement demanding all the anthropogical aspects of being and time" Didi-Huberman

Continuing in the experimentation of photography and generative art.

What's left of what's left ... Seeks to take the reflection beyond the simple superimposition of images, highlighting the "human" x "machine" interaction.

The areas of light, fog and shadows present us with image clippings in a large tangle of visual reflections.

The algorithm builds unique images from the combination of different layers, according to a bank of photographs extracted from my own collection. In total, there are six layers containing 10 photographs each, in addition to a base layer containing 20 photos of urban fragments.

In addition, the code implements, in a random and semi-autonomous way, some adaptations such as masking, colorization, rotation and blending modes for specific layers.

* Features
Place - Where have i been. 20 distinct urban fragments;
Mode - “Color” 80% or “B&W” 20%;
Zone - “Amazon” 25%; “Mist” and “Terracotta” 20%, “Old Sky” 15%; and “Ocher” and “Golden” 10%.
Invert - 2.5%

"In a sense of overlapping past/future, not as an idea of ​​current time, but as places of memory dispute. This "non-place", traversed by layers, is solidified in the images, almost like a truce from the endless war of this inconstancy.
there is no winner" Raffa Gomes

Generative Token by of Morbeck for fxhash

august 21, 2022

metadata.name: The Woodcarver's apprentice #31
metadata.description:
A mix of aesthetics from the Ukiyo-e and Shin-hanga woodblock movements, with modern elements.  

ukiyo-e (浮世絵) = "pictures of the floating world", which peaked in the late 19th century. 
shin-hanga (新版画) = "new prints", from roughly the 1920-1950s. 

Some comparisons between the prints of the Japanese masters and gen-art: 

* The number of prints. Based on how well a piece was received, the publisher could decide to produce more copies, usually in batches of 200. Compare this to limiting the edition size on fx(hash). The initial prints would have sharp lines and accurately coloured areas. Very popular prints with thousands of impressions would slowly degrade the blocks, leaving final prints with worn-out linework and colours that weren't true to originals.  

* Woodblock prints were actually a collab between the artist, the wood carver, and the printer. In many cases only the artist and publisher were recognized on the final prints. It was usually the publisher who owned the woodblock, not the artist. Often the artist was considered a worker, contracted at the request of the publisher or patrons funding the project. Compare this to the NFT space, where ownership is carved onto the blockchain, and artists have freedom to create whatever they wish. 

* Copyminters.... Similar to the NFT world, fake publishers sprang up from time to time, who would reproduce famous prints. Enji Takamizawa was one such counterfeiter, who was able to skilfully produce woodblocks replicating originals down to the wood grain! 

* While fine-quality woodblock prints from the Edo era command huge auction prices today, they were in reality affordable art for the regular people of their time. NFTs are similar in this light, where we can enjoy pieces at home rather than say, visiting galleries or museums of unattainable art. 



Additional querystring params (use when viewing in a separate window) 

* fullsize=true (33 megapixel output) 
* colourcorrect=false 
* grain=false 
* border=false 



Licenses included in source. Relying on: 

* PIXIJS for drawing 
* JSTS for geometry functions 
* chromajs for colour functions 
* noise and gaussian helpers from p5js

metadata.name: Verdant Brut #158
metadata.description:
Verdant translates to “lush, green” and Brut means “dry, raw, or unrefined.”

This series is less about impressions of nature, or vegetal growth… but rather the vibrant, lush world that abstract art can provide and while certain iterations may serve Brutalist aesthetics, it tries to focus on the unrefined/raw aspect of the definition with more fluid shapes that feel irregular and organic in a playful, almost adolescent way.

Palettes inspired by MOMO, Melissa Wiederrecht, Erik Swahn, Marcelo Soria-Rodríguez, Paul Klee, Mareva Millarc, Ernst Mether-Borgström, Douglas Herbert Courtenay Auburn, Jim Harris, Alayne Spafford, Man Ray, Lajos Kassak and William Lachance. While the palettes may not always reflect their trademark colors (if they even have any) they are an homage to individual pieces by the respective artists that have influenced this series in their own way.

4878 bytes of Vanilla JS with no libraries.

For more info on the chosen palettes and other inspirations, see article linked from the main project page: Regarding Verdant Brut

In live mode:
‘S’ : save as png (2376 × 3360)
’V’ : save as svg (without grain)

URL params in live mode:
‘g=n’ : no grain
‘g=p’ : paper grain
‘h=t’ : high resolution mode, 5940 × 8400 (Chrome only)

For example, if you wanted paper grain in high resolution, append “&g=p&h=t” to the url in live mode.

After rendering with these params, tapping 'P' will then save the png with those settings applied.

metadata.name: Departure Within Shattered Windmills #31
metadata.description:
I wrote the following when reviewing the outputs...

The wind is gone,
My windmill falls,
I reach out to catch the pieces.
Half fall in my right hand,
The others in my left,
Two stacks of colored paper.
I’m holding my windmill,
I feel the breeze in my hair.
Each hand is empty,
My windmill rises,
I can see the wind.

'Departure Within Shattered Windmills' was originally inspired by suprematism, and then started to gain more complexity. It is still a combination of simple features, subdivided quads drawn on different planes of perspective. Chaos simulated by many organized grids. Countless pieces of a windmill.

25% of the royalties for each edition will pass to the original minter.

Each output is generated from code written in p5js.

Created by Eric Davidson. 2022.

metadata.name: Dapperu #349
metadata.description:
Go bold, Dapperu!

Dapperu is the first generative animated GIF avatar.

A single Dapperu has 13 traits that result in different colors, shapes and movements. Every Dapperu is unique and can be used as a GIF wherever you like.

You can right-click the image and save it as a GIF file.

You can also press [control / command + s] or [tap and hold outside the image] to save a ZIP file that contains the GIF and all individual frames as SVG images.

© 2022 Dapperu.

metadata.name: Scaffold #42
metadata.description:
The thoughts we have are rarely as ordered as the words we speak and the actions we take are shaped by expectation and conditioning.

As we grow up, we are taught to behave or even think in a certain way. We learn what is acceptable and what is not. Our thoughts are forced to align with the structure imposed upon us.

Scaffold is an attempt to visually explore this concept of thoughts and control. Each output represents a state of mind at a particular moment in time.

Palettes have been mostly named by my family based on the first word they thought of when they saw them.

Keyboard commands:

s - save as png
h - toggle high resolution 
b - toggle background texture
a - switch aspect ratio
r - new moment

metadata.name: a fortiori #455
metadata.description:
Energy is everywhere: it’s moving our bodies, buzzing around a city, growing the universe, and connecting everything within it. Perhaps the strongest symbol humans use for energy – for ideas, life, and the various incarnations of power – is light itself. 

For centuries, each form of art has tried to capture the energetic luminescence of a bright light, a warm glow, a spark... if we could only draw with its pure brilliance! From Caravaggio’s diagonal beams, to Picasso drawing with light across Gjon Mili’s photographic emulsions… this pursuit persists through obsessive efforts by artists of every media. 

a fortiori seeks to capture this power of light with code, output on the native illumination of modern screens. The visual deconstruction of light and its reassembly into a frozen moment produces the tangible shards of each spark – resulting in a sum of marks that exceeds the value of their individual parts. It’s then the obsessive energy of generative art’s looping and controlled randomness that enable its repeated mark making, of all types, to express the nearly-intangible intensity of light.

What one hand might communicate in drawing, with light or stick or keyboard, 100 hands would therefore say 100 times louder, clearer, and more impactfully. And if one could capture the authentic energy of traveling light in a single image, it stands to reason that 500 of these images will multiply their energy-inducing qualities together, and exponentially grow their collective power. In this idea, the medium is the message – proving the power of the medium, and its ability to generate energy.


--------

TENDER x Thomas Noya
December 2022

Source code is licensed under the GNU Lesser General Public License as published by the Free Software Foundation.

a fortiori was created in p5.js and is optimized for live output in Chrome. Press these keys in live view to control the art and render high resolution versions of any token:

x = pause
y = play
1 = 1000x1000
2-9 = 2000x2000, …, 9000x9000
0 = 10000x10000
t = 12500x12500
f = 15000x15000
s = save PNG

Outputs beyond 10,000 pixels square are dependent on individual computer and browser capabilities. 

10% of all primary and secondary proceeds donated directly to Girls Who Code

◉_◉

metadata.name: Layers #12
metadata.description:
It's the first time I really delved into studying about P5JS

I spent the last one collecting generative art and it made my passion for all this just grow, as a collector I wanted to move forward and want to do something more and so developed this project. 

I've been a designer for almost 10 years, an art director for over 1 year, I work all day with design every day, Photoshop and its infinite layers haunt me all day, as my passion wanted to insert something related there in my work so I thought of "layers" and thus "Layers" was born, layers and layers, specifically of rectangles one on top of the other forming the interactions of this work.

5 Styles:

Dunes:
Curves, some sharp and others less so, some remind me of sand dunes.

moiree:
It reminds me a little of compositions with a Moiré effect, forming curves where there is the presence of shadows giving relief.

Arranged:

A style where there is a certain organization of lines, but not perfect.

Strips:

Strips of colors on top of each other.

Harmonic:
It forms flat compositions, they are more organized layers.


17 Color Palettes based on famous works such as paintings and compositions:

"Mondrian - Composition with Large Red Plane, Yellow, Black, Gray and Blue / Piet Mondrian"
"Monalisa - Leonardo da Vinci"
"Portrait - Van Gogh self-portrait / Van Gogh"
"Venus - The Birth of Venus / Sandro Botticelli"
"Memory - The Persistence of Memory / Salvador Dalí"
"Son - The Son of Man /René Magritte"
"Guitarist - The Old Guitarist / Pablo Picasso"
"Canna - Red Canna / Georgia O'Keeffe"
"Drowning - Drowning Girl / Roy Lichtenstein"
"American - American Gothic / Grant Wood"
"Sunrise - Impression, Sunrise / Claude Monet"
"Creation - The Creation of Adam / Michelangelo"
"Girl - Girl with a Pearl Earring / Johannes Vermeer"
"Square - Black Square / Kazimir Malevich"
"Wave - The Great Wave off Kanagawa / Katsushika Hokusai"
"Wanderer - Wanderer above the Sea of ​​Fog / David Friedrich"
"Scream - The Scream / Edvard Munch"

"Layers" uses grains/noises function by Gorilla Sun, thanks for sharing your article with us! Article https://www.fxhash.xyz/article/all-about-that-grain

Created with p5js / Alex Benedith

metadata.name: reborn #61
metadata.description:
This is an album of cities too ideal to ever materialise.

It consists of 256 algorithmically generated plans that resemble drawings of Vincenzo Scamozzi, Pietro Cataneo, Filarete and other theorists of the Italian Renaissance. The cities differ in size, the grid of the streets, the landscape around them and the people that inhabit their utopian walls. They carry names that are Italian exonyms of real European cities, drawing a vision of a different world that enacts a mixture of military perfection with social superiority. Flawless, harmonious, unconquerable and utterly impossible.

History brought us many theories about ideal cities, but very few examples exist today. Italian Palmanova or Polish Zamość are the few to remind us how hard it is to shape reality according to ideals. When confronted with the material world, its idealism becomes the city's grates foe.

To zoom, press a mouse button over the image or touch the screen. To pan, keep the mouse pressed and move it around.

metadata.name: The Spectrum Of Nature #51
metadata.description:
*\_../*`¬-’\/*`¬’’¬`*\/’-¬`*\.._/*

Nature, nature, evolving might… Silent inventor, always right.
Where is the edge of nature and where do we begin?  
What is of nature and what is of man? 
Isn't everything made by nature's hands?

To know more about the concept and technicalities of this piece, see the fxtext article “The spectrum of nature - a short making of”. Link at the bottom. If you’d rather just ignore my personal meaning, feel free to skip the article. 

\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\

Basic info:
The piece comes in possible portrait or landscape versions. Both have a relative size of 1 by 1.5. So the initial render will be 1000px wide and 1500px high for portrait. And 1500x1000 for landscape. With the ability to scale this up (see below).

The piece uses WebGL, so will perform much better with a graphics card. A faster computer will obviously be better, though I've done my very best to make it fast and efficient for any old laptop. My hope is that you will find the render process quick and enjoyable for the amount of detail that’s present. 

../’`*’`\../’`*’`\../’`*’`\../’`*’`\../’`*’`\..

Controls:
Press the [s] key to save the initial render. You will need to wait a few seconds after all the elements have stopped loading. A box will pop up in the top left saying “done” for 4 seconds when it’s ready. For the [s] key to work you may need to open in a new tab. But can right click save otherwise.

Larger sizes:
Press the [2-9] keys to save a resolution of that key size. So [2] saves a 2000x3000 size image, [9] saves a 9000x13500 size image etc. Unless you are making some very large prints you probably won’t need more than 4k (even 2-3k is big). Though the option is there. 

There may be slight variations in the textures for the larger renders, this is because the shader code has to redraw the textures at the higher pixel resolution, and getting the textures where they sit is more of an art than a science. All the elements remain exact however. 

/*/*/*/*/*/*/*/*/*/*/*/*/*/*/*/*/*/*

Made with javascript and some small extra code:
A palette creator by @nathansonic
Noisejs - github.com/josephg/noisejs - Perlin noise generator
Twgl - github.com/greggman/twgl.js - A small webGL helper.
